# List Page Component Style

Use this structure and styling for list/datatable pages (e.g. sp-list, clients-page). Keeps consistent look and feel across the app.

## HTML Structure

```html
<div class="list-container">
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1 class="page-title">{{ pageTitle }}</h1>
  </div>

  <mat-card class="datatable-card">
    <mat-card-content>
      <div class="button-section">
        <button mat-raised-button color="primary" class="add-button" (click)="addItem()">
          <mat-icon>add</mat-icon>
          Добавить
        </button>
      </div>

      <div class="table-header">
        <h3>{{ tableTitle }}</h3>
      </div>

      <div *ngIf="loading" class="loading">Загрузка...</div>
      <table mat-table [dataSource]="items" class="business-table" *ngIf="!loading">
        <ng-container matColumnDef="id">
          <th mat-header-cell *matHeaderCellDef class="col-id">ID</th>
          <td mat-cell *matCellDef="let item" class="col-id">{{ item.id }}</td>
        </ng-container>
        <ng-container matColumnDef="status">
          <th mat-header-cell *matHeaderCellDef align="end" class="col-status">Статус</th>
          <td mat-cell *matCellDef="let item" align="end" class="col-status">
            <span class="status-badge" [ngClass]="getStatusClass(item.status)">
              {{ item.status || 'ACTIVE' }}
            </span>
          </td>
        </ng-container>
        <ng-container matColumnDef="actions">
          <th mat-header-cell *matHeaderCellDef align="end" class="col-actions">...</th>
          <td mat-cell *matCellDef="let item" align="end" class="col-actions">
            <button mat-icon-button (click)="editItem(item, $event)">
              <mat-icon>edit</mat-icon>
            </button>
          </td>
        </ng-container>

        <tr mat-header-row *matHeaderRowDef="displayedColumns"></tr>
        <tr mat-row *matRowDef="let row; columns: displayedColumns"
            (click)="selectRow(row)"
            [class.row-selected]="selectedItem?.id === row.id"
            class="clickable-row"></tr>
      </table>
    </mat-card-content>
  </mat-card>
</div>
```

## Layout Rules

| Element | Style |
|---------|-------|
| **Container** | `padding: 20px`, `max-width: 1200px`, `margin: 0 auto` |
| **Button section** | `display: flex`, `justify-content: flex-end`, button `min-width: 150px` |
| **Actions column** | `align="end"`, `min-width: 50px` or `width: 100px` |
| **Table** | `table-layout: fixed`, `width: 100%` |
| **Rows** | `clickable-row` with hover `background-color: rgba(63, 81, 181, 0.05)` |
| **Status badge** | `status-badge` + `status-active` / `status-suspended` / `status-deleted` |

## Column Widths (optional)

For fixed column layout, add classes and styles:
- `col-id`: `width: 100px`
- `col-name`: `width: 100%` (flexible)
- `col-status`: `width: 100px`
- `col-actions`: `width: 100px`

## Status Badge

Use `status-badge` with dynamic class from `getStatusClass(item.status)`:

```ts
getStatusClass(status: string): string {
  if (status === 'SUSPENDED') return 'status-suspended';
  if (status === 'DELETED') return 'status-deleted';
  return 'status-active';
}
```

## Status Badge Colors

- `status-active`: green (#4caf50)
- `status-suspended`: orange (#ff9800)
- `status-deleted`: red (#f44336)

